@VictorBreazzeal Lets calculate it. Diameter of the earth is 12,742 km. That is an area of 12,751,611,797,744 m^2, which is a circle of of the earth, or one side of the earth facing the sun. Let's guess that average radiance at that angle is 30% and when the sun is straight above it is 1200 Watts per square meter, at the poles maybe 120 Watts m^2.
So about 4,590,580,247,187,840  Watts, or 4590 terawatts. A day that would be 110,160 TWh, so for 365 days 39,216,960 TWh Annually. 

Other online sources say 173,000 tWh for the sun each hour. I'm out because of the  radiance angle i guess.

@OfftheGridKauai "very windy", what does that mean? I looked it up and it is about a average of 6 m/s on your island.
So for a turbine with a sweep area of 1 meter and wind speed of 6m/s, and 20% efficiency, you will obtain 25 watts. More realistically 12 Watts because of cut in/out speeds. So one day you could get 288 Watt hours.
How does that compare to solar? I suspect you could buy a solar panel of 400 Watts for the cost of a turbine. If stationary a solar panel probably averages 50% of that, so 200 Watts. You average 7 hours of sunshine a day, so you would make 1400 Watt hours. And a solar panel will last a lifetime. More solar is usually way better.
